## Behavioral and Social Consequences

### Addiction and Behavioral Changes

Social media use exhibits addictive features, including compulsive checking, craving, and withdrawal symptoms ([Swainston, 2022](https://positivepsychology.com/social-media-effects/)). This addiction can lead to:

- Reduced productivity and social isolation ([Cram.com, 2022](https://www.cram.com/essay/How-Does-Social-Media-Affect-People/FKZHTLH9JX5Q))
- Altered behavior to seek online acceptance, sometimes at the expense of real-world relationships ([Cram.com, 2022](https://www.cram.com/essay/How-Does-Social-Media-Affect-People/FKZHTLH9JX5Q))

### Cyberbullying and Aggression

The rise of cyberbullying on platforms like Facebook, Twitter, and Instagram is a major public health concern, contributing to psychological distress among youth ([Bashir & Bhat, 2016](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/322918815_Effects_of_Social_Media_on_Mental_Health_A_Review)). Approximately 42% of social media users report experiencing cyberbullying annually ([Bartleby.com, 2022](https://www.bartleby.com/essay/The-Negative-Effects-Of-Social-Media-On-FAZDB5YWFR)).

### Impact on Self-Esteem and Body Image

Social media's promotion of social comparison can negatively affect self-esteem and body image, especially among adolescents ([Swainston, 2022](https://positivepsychology.com/social-media-effects/)). Studies show that exposure to idealized images and peer evaluations on social media platforms can lead to unfavorable self-assessments.

